    "body": "Hi,\r\n\r\nCurrently, redcarpet properly converts a non-ASCII header to a hash string (#538). However, when a header contains ASCII and non-ASCII characters, redcarpet simply strips non-ASCII characters. This behavior can create a same ID from different header strings. For example:\r\n\r\n```rb\r\nrequire 'redcarpet'\r\n\r\nrenderer = Redcarpet::Render::HTML.new(with_toc_data: true)\r\nmarkdown = Redcarpet::Markdown.new(renderer)\r\n\r\ninput = <<~MD\r\n  ## Fooの始め方\r\n  ## Fooのインストール\r\nMD\r\n\r\nputs markdown.render(input)\r\n# =>\r\n# <h2 id=\"foo\">Fooの始め方</h2>\r\n# \r\n# <h2 id=\"foo\">Fooのインストール</h2>\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis is a problem especially when I create a TOC. When I render a TOC from the above `input` text, `HTML_TOC` generates anchors for `Fooの始め方` and `Fooのインストール`, but both anchors have a same `href` which links to `#foo`.\r\n\r\nIs there a way to avoid this ID duplication?\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n- ruby: 2.3.1-p112\r\n- redcarpet: 3.4.0"
