    "created_at": "2017-03-02T23:06:39Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-03-03T20:42:07Z",
    "closed_at": "2017-03-03T20:42:07Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "So the [low level rendering](https://github.com/vmg/redcarpet#low-level-rendering) section of the home page mentions an `entity(text)` method.\r\n\r\nI had assumed this method was for escaping stuff in our own custom renderers, but this does not seem to be the case (unless I am obliviously missing something):\r\n\r\n```ruby\r\nclass LinkMark < Redcarpet::Render::HTML\r\n  def link(link, title, content)\r\n    if title && title[0]\r\n      \"<a href=\\\"#{link}\\\" title=\\\"#{entity(title)}\\\">#{content}</a>\"\r\n    else\r\n      \"<a href=\\\"#{link}\\\">#{content}</a>\"\r\n    end\r\n  end\r\nend\r\n```\r\nWhen this is used as a renderer, it results in `NoMethodError: undefined method  'entity' for #<LinkMark:0x00000007495488>`. (Assuming a title.)\r\n\r\nBy the same token, if you just pass the arguments through like so:\r\n```ruby\r\nclass LinkMark < Redcarpet::Render::HTML\r\n  def link(link, title, content)\r\n    if title && title[0]\r\n      \"<a href=\\\"#{link}\\\" title=\\\"#{title}\\\">#{content}</a>\"\r\n    else\r\n      \"<a href=\\\"#{link}\\\">#{content}</a>\"\r\n    end\r\n  end\r\nend\r\n```\r\nyou get:\r\n```ruby\r\nmarkdown = Redcarpet::Markdown.new(ButtonMark)\r\nmarkdown.render(\"[te\\\"st](http://www.google.com \\\"tit\\\"le\\\")\")\r\n# \"<p><a href=\\\"http://www.google.com\\\" title=\\\"tit\\\"le\\\">te&quot;st</a></p>\\n\"\r\n```\r\nwhereas with the built in renderer you get:\r\n```ruby\r\nmarkdown = Redcarpet::Markdown.new(Redcarpet::Render::HTML)\r\nmarkdown.render(\"[te\\\"st](http://www.google.com \\\"tit\\\"le\\\")\")\r\n# \"<p><a href=\\\"http://www.google.com\\\" title=\\\"tit&quot;le\\\">te&quot;st</a></p>\\n\"\r\n```\r\nwhich has smartly escaped the extra internal quotation in both places.\r\n\r\nNow correctly escaping things isn't a problem - I can use any standard HTML entity escaping method to do so if needed. \r\n\r\nMy questions are:\r\n1) Why is `content` pre-escaped and `title` not?  \r\n2) What is the mentioned `entity` method for, and how/when do you use it?\r\n\r\n"
  },
