    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Pandoc has a markdown extension called [`bracketed_spans`](http://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html#extension-bracketed_spans). It allows you to have links without targets, so that you can apply arbitrary attributes:\r\n\r\n    [this is not a link]{this=\"not-link\"}\r\n\r\nThese are then rendered as `<span/>`s with the attributes applied.\r\n\r\nI'd really like this in redcarpet (and thus GitHub) because it makes (human) language tagging much simpler&mdash;the only way to achieve this is at the moment is to drop to HTML-syntax `<span lang=\"foo\">in language foo</span>`, which is not as nice as sticking to Markdown 🙂 (the equivalent\r\nbeing `[in language foo]{lang=\"foo\"}`).\r\n\r\nMotivation: Tagging language in HTML is important due to Han unification (among other things), where [the rendering of a particular character depends on what the target language is](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Han_unification#Examples_of_language-dependent_glyphs):\r\n\r\n![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/12575/21705161/50ec8654-d412-11e6-85b5-1e6fb72b498d.png)\r\n\r\nThanks!"
